WEBVTT

01:26.416 --> 01:28.166
DJ (over radio):
There's your Golden Earring,

01:28.250 --> 01:30.375
and they're gonna be opening
for The Who for three days

01:30.458 --> 01:32.000
at Madison Square Garden, starting...

01:32.083 --> 01:33.708
(radio shuts off)

01:41.708 --> 01:44.125
(typewriter keys clacking)

01:44.208 --> 01:45.625
(typewriter bell dings)

01:45.708 --> 01:47.583
(bird cawing)

01:53.666 --> 01:55.250
Is that Uncle Charlie?

01:55.333 --> 01:57.083
I was trying to fucking help you pitch.

01:57.166 --> 01:58.541
Help me pitch?

01:58.625 --> 02:00.458
This is batting practice, okay?

02:00.541 --> 02:02.375
It's not for you to help me pitch.

02:02.458 --> 02:04.083
I'm worried about you.

02:04.166 --> 02:06.083
(overlapping chatter)

02:06.166 --> 02:08.291
All right, shut the fuck up.

02:08.375 --> 02:10.041
All right, all right, all right. Ready?

02:10.125 --> 02:11.375
Ah, this guy's got nothing.

02:11.458 --> 02:13.166
You got nothing. Come on, Chaz.

02:13.250 --> 02:15.916
-- All right, here we go.
-- Come on, come on, Goose.

02:16.000 --> 02:17.875
Come on, get it by him. Get it by him.

02:18.875 --> 02:20.875
(indistinct chatter)

02:29.333 --> 02:31.333
I'll see you back at the house.

02:32.416 --> 02:34.375
Ruthie's back there, too.

02:34.458 --> 02:36.000
Be a full house.

02:37.000 --> 02:38.541
Okay.

02:41.500 --> 02:43.666
-What are you gonna do?
-Come on, Chaz. Come on.

02:43.750 --> 02:45.708
(chatter continues indistinctly)

02:46.875 --> 02:48.791
Come on.

02:48.875 --> 02:50.750
We're going home.

02:51.833 --> 02:54.916
We're going home. Again.

02:56.000 --> 02:57.541
All right, here you go. Nice grip.

02:57.625 --> 02:59.083
Here you go, kid.

03:00.416 --> 03:02.458
-Use your glove.
-(laughter)

03:13.625 --> 03:15.791
(creaking)

03:20.000 --> 03:21.791
It was 1973,

03:21.875 --> 03:24.500
and after failing
to pay our rent for five months,

03:24.583 --> 03:28.000
my mom and I had to move
back home to my grandpa's house.

03:28.083 --> 03:29.791
(sighs)

03:37.583 --> 03:41.125
Home never meant the same thing
to my mother as it did to me.

03:41.208 --> 03:44.708
To her, it meant failure,
the place you ended up

03:44.791 --> 03:47.416
when all the things
she was counting on fell through.

03:47.500 --> 03:51.666
Work, apartment, boyfriend,
not always in that order.

03:52.666 --> 03:54.833
But I loved it.

03:54.916 --> 03:58.958
To me, Grandpa's house was
a revolving door of cousins and aunts,

03:59.041 --> 04:01.791
with a full complement
of laughter and tears

04:01.875 --> 04:04.125
and an occasional nervous breakdown.

04:04.208 --> 04:07.625
But above all,
it's where Uncle Charlie lived.

04:07.708 --> 04:10.916
And when you're 11 years old,
you want an Uncle Charlie.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.958
Everybody needs to know
the cesspool isn't taking it.

04:15.041 --> 04:18.583
If you take a leak, take it outside.

04:19.666 --> 04:21.750
I could use a little help in here.

04:23.000 --> 04:24.541
I'm not the maid.

04:25.666 --> 04:26.958
Jesus Christ!

04:27.041 --> 04:29.833
My father was a radio DJ in New York.

04:29.916 --> 04:31.791
They called him The Voice.

04:31.875 --> 04:35.458
He played Top 40 hits,
and he'd talk about the musicians.

04:35.541 --> 04:37.583
I only met him once,
and I was pretty young,

04:37.666 --> 04:42.083
so when I could, I'd sneak away
and listen to him on the radio.

04:42.166 --> 04:45.083
I had to sneak, 'cause after he left us,

04:45.166 --> 04:49.833
well, let's just say Mom took a pair
of scissors to every picture he was in.

04:49.916 --> 04:51.916
(laughter, indistinct chatter over TV)

04:54.833 --> 04:56.458
(over radio):

04:56.541 --> 04:58.458
-(children laughing)

05:13.875 --> 05:16.416
(indistinct sportscast playing)

05:18.583 --> 05:20.583
(Mom sniffling, sobbing softly)

05:27.500 --> 05:29.750
(sighs)

05:29.833 --> 05:31.125
I like it.

05:31.208 --> 05:33.375
(Mom sighs)

05:33.458 --> 05:34.875
Do you?

05:34.958 --> 05:37.291
It's people. I like to have people.

05:45.625 --> 05:48.291
(sighs)
Tomorrow is another day.

05:50.041 --> 05:52.416
Why does Grandpa say
we should all clear out?

05:52.500 --> 05:57.041
Because he's a selfish old prick
who resents taking care of his family.

05:58.208 --> 05:59.791
Like Dad?

05:59.875 --> 06:01.291
No, honey.

06:01.375 --> 06:04.166
Grandpa resents taking care of his family.

06:04.250 --> 06:08.291
Your father has never
taken care of anybody at all.

06:10.875 --> 06:12.416
Oh.

06:12.500 --> 06:14.125
(softly):
Oh.

06:15.958 --> 06:18.166
("Love Will Find a Way" by Pablo Cruise
playing over radio)

06:18.250 --> 06:20.791
(indistinct, overlapping chatter)

06:32.500 --> 06:34.458
(indistinct chatter continues)

06:34.541 --> 06:37.625
That's Pablo Cruise
with "Love Will Find a Way"...

06:37.708 --> 06:39.750
-(radio clatters)
-(broadcast cuts out)

06:39.833 --> 06:41.583
(chatter stops)

06:47.708 --> 06:49.541
Hey, now, eat your cereal.

06:54.166 --> 06:55.791
Okay, two rules.

06:55.875 --> 06:57.791
I'm never gonna let you win, ever.

06:57.875 --> 07:00.458
You beat me,
you know you beat me fair and square,

07:00.541 --> 07:02.333
but I never let you win.

07:02.416 --> 07:04.208
And I'm gonna always tell you the truth.

07:06.166 --> 07:08.041
I saw you in the yard playing sports.

07:08.125 --> 07:09.416
You're not very good.

07:09.500 --> 07:12.708
And... probably not gonna get
a whole lot better,

07:12.791 --> 07:17.833
so it might be wise for you,
in order to avoid tears and disappointment

07:17.916 --> 07:20.750
and, above all, delusion,

07:20.833 --> 07:22.708
you know, find some other activities
that you like.

07:22.791 --> 07:25.000
You know, like, uh,
what do you like to do the most?

07:25.083 --> 07:26.083
I like to read.

07:26.166 --> 07:28.458
I also like to read.

07:28.541 --> 07:30.500
I mean, I'm good at sports, too, but...

07:30.583 --> 07:33.541
So, this thing about the radio.

07:33.625 --> 07:36.625
You're gonna look
for your father in the radio.

07:36.708 --> 07:39.541
You think your father is in the radio.

07:39.625 --> 07:41.666
He's not in the radio.

07:41.750 --> 07:46.375
He's just an asshole
who happens to be on the radio.

07:46.458 --> 07:49.041
Don't look for your father to save you.

07:51.083 --> 07:53.000
And don't play sports.

07:53.083 --> 07:55.083
That's all I have to say.

07:55.166 --> 07:56.666
The game is five-card stud.

07:57.666 --> 07:59.666
(dog barking in distance)

08:03.000 --> 08:05.333
Mom can use some money.

08:05.416 --> 08:09.541
This is The Voice at 97.1 on your dial.

08:09.625 --> 08:11.625
She's really tired after work.

08:11.708 --> 08:14.583
â€¦top ten songs this week, you'll win a Q97

08:14.666 --> 08:16.625
limited-edition brass belt buckle,

08:16.708 --> 08:20.125
and you'll be registered to win $500.

08:20.208 --> 08:22.416
What do you say? The top ten.

08:22.500 --> 08:25.666
You can't win if you don't play.

08:28.125 --> 08:30.083
Is this seat taken?

08:30.166 --> 08:32.416
No.

08:34.666 --> 08:36.583
(sighs)

08:43.958 --> 08:45.958
(railway crossing bells clanging)

08:47.833 --> 08:49.833
Tell your cousin

08:49.916 --> 08:52.458
I said you can ride the fucking bike.

08:52.541 --> 08:55.250
It's not his fucking bike anyway.

08:55.333 --> 08:58.416
It's a house bike.
I took that bike out of the dump

08:58.500 --> 09:00.416
and fixed it up
for all you little assholes.

09:00.500 --> 09:01.833
Now they're moving to Colorado.

09:01.916 --> 09:03.791
It's your bike anyway.

09:03.875 --> 09:06.583
(sighing):
Oh, Jesus, mother of God.

09:06.666 --> 09:08.291
How did you get sick?

09:08.375 --> 09:10.250
I'm not sick.

09:10.333 --> 09:12.708
It's Saturday morning.

09:12.791 --> 09:15.541
This is the way it is.

09:15.625 --> 09:19.541
This is Saturday morning
in the life of men.

09:19.625 --> 09:21.333
Oh.

09:21.416 --> 09:23.916
Go around to the bar.
Get me a pack of cigarettes.

09:25.291 --> 09:27.291
(phone ringing)

09:29.166 --> 09:31.625
Get that before your grandmother does.

09:31.708 --> 09:34.375
I'm-I'm not here. Whoever...

09:34.458 --> 09:36.625
-Hello?
-Hey.

09:36.708 --> 09:40.500
Now, I know there are a lot
of rug rats running around,

09:40.583 --> 09:43.458
but I'm wondering if this is JR.

09:43.541 --> 09:44.791
Dad?

09:44.875 --> 09:45.916
Huh? What?

09:46.000 --> 09:47.500
That's right, buddy, if this is JR...

09:47.583 --> 09:49.541
Give me the fucking phone.

09:49.625 --> 09:51.500
-...I'm your father.
-Mom's not here.

09:51.583 --> 09:53.416
Well, I'm not calling
for your mother, kiddo.

09:53.500 --> 09:54.666
I'm calling for you.

09:54.750 --> 09:57.208
Hey, uh...

09:57.291 --> 09:59.791
How would you like to see
a ball game with your old man?

09:59.875 --> 10:03.125
-Really?
-Sure. Ball game with your old man.

10:03.208 --> 10:05.000
Mets or Yankees?

10:05.083 --> 10:06.541
Whatever you like.

10:06.625 --> 10:08.791
Uncle Charlie says
the Yankees are assholes,

10:08.875 --> 10:10.791
but the Mets drink at The Dickens.

10:11.875 --> 10:13.541
How is your Uncle Charlie?

10:13.625 --> 10:15.208
How are you? He wants to know.

10:15.291 --> 10:17.125
I'm still short 30 bucks.

10:20.750 --> 10:23.208
Tell him the Mets play the Braves
tomorrow night.

10:23.291 --> 10:25.458
Mets play the Braves tomorrow night.

10:25.541 --> 10:26.916
Doesn't mean he's gonna show up.

10:27.000 --> 10:28.958
Well, I will tell you what, sport.

10:29.041 --> 10:30.916
I'll get a couple tickets. (clears throat)

10:31.000 --> 10:33.333
And I will pick you up
at your grandfather's at30.

10:33.416 --> 10:34.791
Great. Thank you.

10:34.875 --> 10:37.083
We got a lot
to catch up on, you and me.

10:37.166 --> 10:38.291
Okay.

10:38.375 --> 10:40.166
-Bye, now.
-Bye.

10:42.666 --> 10:44.291
You gonna get my cigarettes?

10:44.375 --> 10:45.541
Oh.

10:47.166 --> 10:49.000
Are you reading this paper?

10:49.083 --> 10:50.500
-Oh, no.
-Great.

10:57.958 --> 10:59.333
(chuckles softly)

10:59.416 --> 11:01.708
I... I got an interview at Yale.

11:01.791 --> 11:03.583
(chuckles)

11:16.708 --> 11:18.708
He said to be ready at- 30.

11:18.791 --> 11:22.250
I was ready at30 so as not to fuck up.

11:22.333 --> 11:25.333
You always remember fucking up,
so you don't want to.

11:26.833 --> 11:30.666
The thing is, that day, I felt like I had.

11:30.750 --> 11:32.875
That's the thing to remember about a kid.

11:32.958 --> 11:35.500
The kid always thinks he fucked up.

11:36.875 --> 11:38.500
I didn't know what he looked like.

11:38.583 --> 11:42.208
I hadn't been to New York City
to see his face on billboards and buses.

11:42.291 --> 11:44.708
I couldn't have picked him out of a crowd.

11:44.791 --> 11:47.916
But I wondered if it was like
a thing you would always know,

11:48.000 --> 11:50.791
as if you would always know
your father instantly.

11:51.875 --> 11:53.375
It was possible.

11:57.625 --> 11:59.791
-(crickets chirping)
-(dog barking in distance)

11:59.875 --> 12:01.875
(vehicle approaching)

12:01.958 --> 12:03.958
(brakes squeaking)

12:07.291 --> 12:09.416
-(engine shuts off)
-(door opens)

12:09.500 --> 12:11.333
(door closes)

12:13.041 --> 12:15.458
A little while later,
after being arrested while on air

12:15.541 --> 12:18.333
for nonpayment of child support,

12:18.416 --> 12:20.333
The Voice fled the state.

12:21.750 --> 12:24.291
It was about this same period
that he called up drunk

12:24.375 --> 12:27.416
and said he put a contract
on my mother's life.

12:27.500 --> 12:29.083
He also threatened to kidnap me,

12:29.166 --> 12:31.708
but Uncle Charlie thought
this was a less serious threat,

12:31.791 --> 12:34.333
as kidnapping comes with responsibilities.

12:36.833 --> 12:38.875
We're the Two Musketeers, right?

12:40.500 --> 12:41.833
Yeah.

12:41.916 --> 12:44.375
("Shotgun" by Jr. Walker & The All Stars
playing)

12:48.708 --> 12:50.708
Let me show you something, okay?

12:50.791 --> 12:53.666
This is the male sciences, all right?

12:53.750 --> 12:55.416
You get your drink.

12:55.500 --> 12:57.208
That goes there.

12:57.291 --> 12:59.833
Got your pack of butts, right?

12:59.916 --> 13:01.708
That goes there.

13:01.791 --> 13:03.833
See that? Look at...
look at this guy right there.

13:03.916 --> 13:06.333
See how he's putting his money
in his pocket like that?

13:06.416 --> 13:07.583
-Yeah.
-Never do that.

13:07.666 --> 13:09.333
That's keeping your money like a drunk.

13:09.416 --> 13:10.625
It's not correct.

13:10.708 --> 13:13.125
Know what you also do?

13:13.208 --> 13:14.958
You take care of your mother.

13:15.041 --> 13:16.916
All right?

13:17.000 --> 13:18.458
All right, give me a hand.

13:18.541 --> 13:21.666
And you take care of,
if you have one, your woman.

13:21.750 --> 13:23.708
If you drink, you keep your shit together.

13:23.791 --> 13:25.833
If your shit's not together,
you don't drink.

13:25.916 --> 13:27.791
Don't be like one of these assholes here
who acts like

13:27.875 --> 13:29.958
it was Jesus who came down
and made him late for work

13:30.041 --> 13:31.833
and spend all their money and throw back

13:31.916 --> 13:34.125
Old Hammerhead with vanilla Coke
for 30 years.

13:34.208 --> 13:36.791
You know what I'm saying?
It's about being a man.

13:36.875 --> 13:39.708
Get your drink. You get your butts.

13:39.791 --> 13:43.375
Don't carry your money like a drunk.
Oh, and, uh...

13:43.458 --> 13:46.333
See this? This little compartment
in your wallet, right?

13:46.416 --> 13:48.666
That's where you keep your stashies.

13:48.750 --> 13:51.208
That's like a hundred bucks,
five, whatever,

13:51.291 --> 13:53.250
depending on the economy.

13:53.333 --> 13:57.500
Important thing is you never,
ever drink that money, right?

13:57.583 --> 13:59.500
What else? Hold doors.

13:59.583 --> 14:01.083
Be good to your mother.

14:01.166 --> 14:03.375
Teach you how to change a tire,
jump a car.

14:03.458 --> 14:04.750
You know, that's it.

14:04.833 --> 14:07.708
Change a tire, jump a car, take care
of your mother, don't drink your stashies.

14:07.791 --> 14:11.000
Oh, one more thing-- very important.

14:11.083 --> 14:14.250
Never under any circumstances hit a woman,

14:14.333 --> 14:16.791
even if she stabs you with scissors.

14:16.875 --> 14:17.916
Got it.

14:18.000 --> 14:20.708
That's it. Male sciences. Right.

14:22.041 --> 14:23.708
Can people read those books?

14:23.791 --> 14:25.875
Can they read...

14:25.958 --> 14:27.583
What are you, soft?

14:27.666 --> 14:29.041
No, I mean, can I read them?

14:29.125 --> 14:30.416
What's the name of this place?

14:30.500 --> 14:31.750
The Dickens.

14:31.833 --> 14:33.666
That's right.

14:35.000 --> 14:37.458
Charles Dickens. You know who that is?

14:37.541 --> 14:39.083
-The owner?
-(chuckles)

14:40.166 --> 14:42.208
Yes, you can read 'em.
You can read as many as you like.

14:42.291 --> 14:43.833
Take 'em in the poker room. Read 'em all.

14:43.916 --> 14:45.541
Fill yourself up.

14:45.625 --> 14:47.458
And you know what might happen?

14:47.541 --> 14:51.166
If you read enough books,
maybe, if you're lucky,

14:51.250 --> 14:53.458
you could become a writer.

14:54.791 --> 14:56.541
And that was it.

14:56.625 --> 15:00.083
From that moment on,
I wanted to be a writer.

15:00.166 --> 15:01.333
(jingle playing over radio)

15:01.416 --> 15:04.083
GRANDPA (singing along):

15:07.291 --> 15:09.333
Apricots.

15:10.416 --> 15:13.250
-(passes gas)
-Ah. I didn't do that.

15:13.333 --> 15:16.250
Your grandfather has
a photographic memory.

15:16.333 --> 15:19.000
He knows Greek and Latin.

15:19.083 --> 15:21.750
But here is this-- the furniture is
held together with duct tape,

15:21.833 --> 15:24.250
and he's doing this--
he's farting and saying he didn't do it,

15:24.333 --> 15:27.208
saying "apricots" for no reason.

15:27.291 --> 15:29.041
That's what he did with going to college.

15:29.125 --> 15:31.958
And yet you all end up back here.

15:32.041 --> 15:34.750
You are a stingy, crazy, old bastard.

15:34.833 --> 15:36.125
You are not stingy with money.

15:36.208 --> 15:37.416
Haven't got any.

15:37.500 --> 15:40.875
-You are stingy with love.
-(passes gas)

15:40.958 --> 15:42.500
I didn't do that.

15:42.583 --> 15:44.708
Girls become wives and mothers.
That was his point of view.

15:44.791 --> 15:47.458
-You became one of them.
-Oh, shut up, you old turd!

15:47.541 --> 15:49.458
-(scoffs)
-Because he is stingy

15:49.541 --> 15:52.083
with love and understanding,
that is why I have no education,

15:52.166 --> 15:54.166
and that is why you--

15:54.250 --> 15:57.333
I swear to God, I have no idea how--

15:57.416 --> 15:59.750
you are going to Harvard or Yale.

15:59.833 --> 16:01.708
-(passes gas)
-I didn't do that.

16:01.791 --> 16:03.458
You are going to Harvard or Yale.

16:03.541 --> 16:05.125
Make up for your disappointments?

16:05.208 --> 16:07.125
-Harvard or Yale.
-This from a woman

16:07.208 --> 16:09.333
who earns 30 bucks a day.

16:09.416 --> 16:13.083
And after college-- at Harvard or Yale!--

16:13.166 --> 16:15.250
you are going to law school.

16:15.333 --> 16:17.833
So you can sue your father
for child support.

16:17.916 --> 16:20.833
No, so he can help you
with your fines about the septic tank.

16:20.916 --> 16:22.666
(passes gas)

16:27.791 --> 16:29.291
(engine shuts off)

16:29.375 --> 16:31.000
(door opens)

16:32.500 --> 16:34.125
(door closes)

16:47.875 --> 16:51.958
Fregosi is the hitter
facing the right-hander Jenkins.

16:52.041 --> 16:53.833
Infield playing in.

16:53.916 --> 16:55.416
Here comes the pitch.

16:55.500 --> 16:58.416
Fastball is in there for a strike,
and it's two and two.

16:58.500 --> 17:01.166
(chuckles, mutters)
What the fuck is this?

17:01.250 --> 17:03.708
Hey, Charlie. How's it hanging?

17:03.791 --> 17:05.125
Still got the clap, asshole?

17:05.208 --> 17:06.875
You know I got it from your sister.

17:06.958 --> 17:09.583
-Where's my 30 bucks?
-It's up my ass. Come get it.

17:09.666 --> 17:11.833
JR, say hi to your father.

17:11.916 --> 17:14.750
Jenkins sets, looks in and delivers.

17:14.833 --> 17:16.958
-Swing and a miss! Strike three.
-(car door closes)

17:17.041 --> 17:19.125
-And away we go.
-(engine starts)

17:19.208 --> 17:20.833
("A Long Time Ago" by Jim Croce playing)

17:37.958 --> 17:40.375
You like living
at your grandfather's house?

17:40.458 --> 17:41.625
Yeah.

17:41.708 --> 17:43.833
I mean... no.

17:46.208 --> 17:47.416
Yes or no?

17:47.500 --> 17:49.833
I mean, I like it, but Mom doesn't.

17:51.291 --> 17:54.458
Well, I think your grandfather
is a good man.

17:54.541 --> 17:58.541
Marches to his own drummer,
but that's what I like about him.

17:59.625 --> 18:01.958
Mom says he might have lost his mind.

18:03.000 --> 18:07.166
Well, there's that, too.
Sometimes your own drummer is a bad idea.

18:12.000 --> 18:15.250
It makes Mom sad having to keep
going to Grandpa's house.

18:18.708 --> 18:20.458
She blame me?

18:25.166 --> 18:27.208
See, the thing about women...

18:29.500 --> 18:33.375
Sometimes they don't think about
the cause and effect of things.

18:33.458 --> 18:36.125
They want freedom,

18:36.208 --> 18:40.416
but then they blame you
for dispensing it once they get it.

18:41.791 --> 18:44.125
At least that's my experience.

18:44.208 --> 18:47.250
One swinging dick to another.
I'll give you that one.

18:49.875 --> 18:54.333
Hey, your mom tells me you listen
to your old man on the radio a lot.

18:54.416 --> 18:57.458
She says I listen too much
or try to find you.

18:58.500 --> 19:01.166
-You change stations a lot.
-(chuckles)

19:01.250 --> 19:03.458
That's the management.

19:03.541 --> 19:06.041
You want to be a disc jockey
when you grow up?

19:06.125 --> 19:08.458
-I'm gonna be a lawyer.
-Jesus. Why?

19:08.541 --> 19:10.208
Mom wants me to.

19:11.500 --> 19:14.166
Talk a lot of shit and believe anything.

19:16.625 --> 19:18.958
All right.

19:19.041 --> 19:21.000
Good to see you, young man.

19:22.750 --> 19:26.041
-I got a barbecue meeting with a sponsor.
-(music stops)

19:26.125 --> 19:27.875
-Can I come?
-Nope.

19:32.166 --> 19:34.958
Tell your mother not to spend that all
in one place.

19:36.250 --> 19:40.541
As for you, keep listening to the radio.

19:40.625 --> 19:43.333
See you soon, Junior.

19:43.416 --> 19:46.166
A doctor at school says
I have no identity.

19:46.250 --> 19:47.666
Jesus. (laughs)

19:47.750 --> 19:49.000
Get one.

19:49.083 --> 19:50.916
I'll see you on the flip side.

19:57.958 --> 19:59.375
See ya.

20:04.333 --> 20:06.250
Hey, asshole.

20:06.333 --> 20:08.625
Good day with the kid?

20:08.708 --> 20:10.916
Fuck you, Charlie.

20:11.000 --> 20:13.916
Give me my 30 bucks
or get the fuck out of the car.

20:15.708 --> 20:17.333
Hey, don't be a fucking... You know what?

20:17.416 --> 20:19.208
Don't be trying to be
a fucking tough guy, all right?

20:19.291 --> 20:20.958
(grunts)

20:21.041 --> 20:23.125
Why'd you marry him?

20:23.208 --> 20:24.791
I was young.

20:25.875 --> 20:27.875
I was dumb.

20:27.958 --> 20:30.125
I don't want to be a junior.

20:30.208 --> 20:32.416
I don't want to have the same name.

20:36.166 --> 20:37.916
(Mom sniffles)

20:39.750 --> 20:42.458
You can have any name you want.

20:42.541 --> 20:45.083
("Magic" by Pilot playing)

20:45.166 --> 20:47.541
Who was the guy
pitched a no-hitter on acid?

20:47.625 --> 20:49.083
-- Dock Ellis.
-- You can take acid,

20:49.166 --> 20:51.166
you can take fucking Drano.
You know what I'm saying?

20:51.250 --> 20:52.916
But you commit. You make a decision.

20:53.000 --> 20:54.583
You shit or wind your watch.

20:54.666 --> 20:58.500
You fucking call it a day
or run for president, and that's it.

21:04.166 --> 21:06.083
What do you need me to do?

21:06.166 --> 21:08.958
-(sighs) Mom can't go to something.
-Oh.

21:09.041 --> 21:10.583
I mean, what can't she go to?

21:10.666 --> 21:12.208
Where we going?

21:15.833 --> 21:18.375
Sorry to make you wait.

21:18.458 --> 21:21.375
(sighs) How can I help?

21:21.458 --> 21:23.375
Uh, well, I'm not sure.

21:23.458 --> 21:27.708
Uh, someone said he was having,
uh, tantrums.

21:27.791 --> 21:29.833
Maybe you said that.

21:29.916 --> 21:32.583
His mother's a secretary.
She's busy. She's not here, so I came.

21:32.666 --> 21:35.208
Maybe you can tell me
what this is all about.

21:35.291 --> 21:37.500
The boy won't tell me
what his name stands for.

21:37.583 --> 21:39.875
Doesn't stand for anything.
His name is JR.

21:39.958 --> 21:41.541
Deal with it.

21:42.625 --> 21:44.291
(chuckles softly)

21:50.125 --> 21:54.083
Maybe this is a weird time for me
to tell you that I'm not a psychologist.

21:54.166 --> 21:55.333
Why do you say that?

21:55.416 --> 21:57.083
Well, because I'm not a psychologist

21:57.166 --> 21:59.750
and I'm sitting here with somebody
who actually is a psychologist

21:59.833 --> 22:01.375
who maybe knows I'm not a psychologist.

22:01.458 --> 22:03.083
What are you, fucking inert?

22:09.041 --> 22:10.958
(chuckles) All right.

22:11.041 --> 22:13.458
This is your thing?

22:13.541 --> 22:16.875
Nothing is face value,
and you're the smartest guy in the room,

22:16.958 --> 22:20.875
and you sit there looking for errors
in baseline perception.

22:20.958 --> 22:22.833
Oh, yeah. We all have our jobs.

22:22.916 --> 22:24.958
You have yours. Knock yourself out.

22:25.041 --> 22:26.333
JR-- those are his initials?

22:26.416 --> 22:28.125
Or it's the contraction for "junior."

22:28.208 --> 22:29.541
What fucking difference does it make?

22:29.625 --> 22:32.208
Well, there's a very big difference
if it is being concealed from him

22:32.291 --> 22:34.666
that he's a junior
because there is no senior in his life.

22:34.750 --> 22:37.041
That may never
have occurred to him until you just

22:37.125 --> 22:40.958
laid your line of bullshit
on the subject to him right to his face.

22:41.041 --> 22:45.291
It is my belief that the uncertainty
about the meaning of his name

22:45.375 --> 22:48.541
and the continual questions about it
have left him without identity.

22:48.625 --> 22:52.500
Very impressive.
No identity, hence identity crisis.

22:52.583 --> 22:55.083
He has no identity, which causes rage.

22:55.166 --> 22:59.041
He has dubiety
about his identity, possibly.

23:00.125 --> 23:03.708
How sure are you about your identity? Hmm?

23:03.791 --> 23:06.791
I'm curious because
you seem very interested

23:06.875 --> 23:08.958
in his father and his absence,

23:09.041 --> 23:11.666
and you cast it
in this very negative light

23:11.750 --> 23:15.000
and bring the kid in here
and you're traumatizing him.

23:15.083 --> 23:18.500
We both know you're calling his mother up
and asking her out on dates.

23:22.000 --> 23:23.750
Um, that's...

23:23.833 --> 23:25.833
So you're willing to traumatize
a little kid

23:25.916 --> 23:27.875
in order to hit on his mother?

23:30.416 --> 23:33.291
Uncle Charlie never had
the money to go to college.

23:33.375 --> 23:35.083
He was self-taught.

23:35.166 --> 23:39.041
But that didn't mean some dime-store
fifth-grade shrink could go toe to toe.

23:39.125 --> 23:40.250
(typewriter bell dings)

23:40.333 --> 23:42.333
(clock ticking)

23:47.541 --> 23:50.291
(sighs) The Family Gazette.

23:52.833 --> 23:55.000
This is great, JR.

24:10.958 --> 24:12.958
(sighs)

24:16.250 --> 24:17.916
(lighter flicks)

24:18.000 --> 24:20.291
Okay.

24:20.375 --> 24:22.208
Here it is.

24:22.291 --> 24:25.041
Lose the drawings. Just get rid of 'em.

24:25.125 --> 24:27.750
I know a lot of guys
that think they're writers,

24:27.833 --> 24:30.500
and you'll find in life
that most of them are not.

24:31.833 --> 24:33.458
Here's the thing.

24:33.541 --> 24:35.833
You got to have "it."

24:35.916 --> 24:40.458
I don't know what it is,
but if you don't have it immediately...

24:42.125 --> 24:43.916
...you never get it.

24:50.041 --> 24:51.666
And I say you got it.

24:51.750 --> 24:54.166
Oh. I knew it.

24:54.250 --> 24:55.541
Oh, I knew it! I knew it.

24:55.625 --> 24:57.750
There's-there's... there's something.

24:57.833 --> 24:59.708
Calm down. I didn't say you were good.

24:59.791 --> 25:02.000
I said, you know, you could be.

25:02.083 --> 25:04.083
Come here. Come with me.

25:05.375 --> 25:06.500
(door slides open)

25:06.583 --> 25:10.250
Now, what you do is you read all of those.

25:11.708 --> 25:14.708
Now, I don't want to talk to you
unless you read all those.

25:14.791 --> 25:17.250
I also don't want to talk to you
about all those.

25:25.500 --> 25:27.625
So, Yale interview?

25:27.708 --> 25:29.583
(chuckles) Yeah.

25:30.666 --> 25:32.833
Your mother must be thrilled.

25:32.916 --> 25:34.708
(laughs)

25:34.791 --> 25:37.500
Yeah, you know, it's all she ever wanted.

25:37.583 --> 25:41.416
In my official capacity,
I have to say, is the only thing

25:41.500 --> 25:43.875
to concentrate on in this world

25:43.958 --> 25:47.125
is the desire to see
the face of God the Father.

25:48.500 --> 25:49.750
Right.

25:49.833 --> 25:52.375
However, the Church is on her last legs.

25:52.458 --> 25:55.375
Three people come to my mass.

25:56.625 --> 25:59.541
I had four, but Mrs. Cafferty took a fall

25:59.625 --> 26:02.291
because she didn't have a good son.

26:03.500 --> 26:05.000
Be a good son.

26:05.083 --> 26:06.708
(chuckles softly)

26:06.791 --> 26:08.583
That's why I'm going to the interview.

26:08.666 --> 26:12.083
Now, tell me, when was the last time
you made a good confession?

26:12.166 --> 26:14.250
("Turn Back the Hands of Time"
by Tyrone Davis playing)

26:14.333 --> 26:15.958
Not in my Yale essay.

26:16.041 --> 26:18.000
Well, you want to get in.

26:18.083 --> 26:20.166
(chuckles) Right.

26:22.333 --> 26:23.958
Hey. Whose kid is that?

26:24.041 --> 26:25.958
My sister's.

26:26.041 --> 26:28.291
Which sister?
The hot one or the crazy one?

26:28.375 --> 26:30.500
What, are you fucking stupid?
You want to die?

26:30.583 --> 26:32.291
(laughing)

26:35.666 --> 26:37.416
Hey, get that kid a drink on me.

26:38.583 --> 26:42.291
Oh, you're backed up on Bobo.

26:42.375 --> 26:45.708
You know, I got a feeling that, uh,
you had a reason to come down here.

26:45.791 --> 26:47.166
You didn't just come down here
to come here.

26:47.250 --> 26:49.750
Maybe you forgot.

26:49.833 --> 26:52.083
Grandpa needs a pack of Old Golds.

26:52.166 --> 26:54.875
Never keep somebody away
from their cigarettes.

26:54.958 --> 26:57.125
Poor old guy's probably
climbing the walls.

26:57.208 --> 27:00.291
Well, you know he's gonna be back in here
saying weird shit. Here you go.

27:06.000 --> 27:07.833
I want to back up Bobo.

27:07.916 --> 27:10.333
(light laughter)

27:10.416 --> 27:12.250
With your grandfather's money?

27:12.333 --> 27:13.333
Yeah.

27:14.583 --> 27:16.041
All right.

27:16.125 --> 27:19.166
-Bobo, you're backed up on the kid.
-This kid's all right.

27:20.916 --> 27:23.125
Today, we're gonna take a break
from our studies,

27:23.208 --> 27:25.166
and we're gonna make invitations.

27:25.250 --> 27:29.041
Handmade invitations for
the father-and-son breakfast.

27:29.125 --> 27:31.666
All right, so you're gonna make
your own invitations.

27:31.750 --> 27:33.916
You're gonna bring 'em home
to your fathers after school.

27:34.000 --> 27:38.583
Saturday morning,
we're gonna cook them breakfast,

27:38.666 --> 27:41.500
and you're gonna read to them
from your schoolwork,

27:41.583 --> 27:43.541
so everybody gets to know
each other better.

27:43.625 --> 27:47.916
All right, and I want you to do things
that you do with your dad, all right?

27:48.000 --> 27:50.625
Who needs a scissor? Who needs,
like, a colored pencil or something?

27:50.708 --> 27:53.500
Hold on a sec. Let me get those.

27:53.583 --> 27:56.041
All right? Got that?

27:56.125 --> 27:57.625
(school bell ringing)

27:57.708 --> 28:00.666
All right, guys,
put invitations on my desk.

28:00.750 --> 28:03.250
Thank you, Michael, Stephen.

28:03.333 --> 28:05.041
Adam, excellent.

28:05.125 --> 28:06.666
I love that.

28:06.750 --> 28:08.333
All right.

28:11.416 --> 28:12.875
What is it, JR?

28:12.958 --> 28:14.416
I don't have a father.

28:15.500 --> 28:18.083
Oh. Did he pass on?

28:18.166 --> 28:19.791
I don't know. Maybe.

28:19.875 --> 28:21.541
I just don't have one.

28:21.625 --> 28:22.958
"Passing on" means dead.

28:23.041 --> 28:24.916
Oh. No, he's not dead.

28:25.000 --> 28:26.458
He's on the radio.

28:26.541 --> 28:29.250
Can I just not come to the breakfast?

28:30.291 --> 28:32.208
You know what, I'm gonna call your mother.

28:32.291 --> 28:34.708
-Okay.
-Okay.

28:34.791 --> 28:37.208
Don't they know
the way the world is today?

28:37.291 --> 28:40.958
It's hard to tell people
about your father, JR, because...

28:41.041 --> 28:43.208
it's hard to know where to begin.

28:43.291 --> 28:45.083
Maybe the police can make him go?

28:45.166 --> 28:48.708
-(Mom laughs)
-Police can't make him pay support.

28:48.791 --> 28:51.916
A father-son breakfast might be tough.

28:52.000 --> 28:55.083
Well, why don't you take him,
you son of a bitch?

28:57.083 --> 28:58.500
Ah.

28:59.625 --> 29:02.250
Why not? Why not?

29:02.333 --> 29:04.208
(chuckles)
Oh, you're gonna take him?

29:06.625 --> 29:09.250
("Two of a Kind" by Bobby Darin
& Johnny Mercer playing)

29:43.458 --> 29:45.208
You two look so handsome.

29:53.083 --> 29:54.916
I remember you.

30:07.458 --> 30:10.625
Let's go, before I change my mind.

30:13.291 --> 30:15.125
You have fun.

30:15.208 --> 30:16.916
-Take it easy, kid.
-(door opens)

30:17.000 --> 30:19.291
-(door closes)

30:19.375 --> 30:21.000
-(breath shuddering)

30:21.083 --> 30:22.541
Oh, here we go.

30:59.875 --> 31:03.166
Our educational system, and indeed

31:03.250 --> 31:05.375
our society as a whole,

31:05.458 --> 31:09.958
was destroyed in the 19th century
by the German influence.

31:10.041 --> 31:11.333
Really?

31:11.416 --> 31:17.208
Ability as a concept, turned into
a mechanical, empirical construct.

31:17.291 --> 31:20.875
You may be a beneficiary of this system.

31:20.958 --> 31:25.458
Regardless of the system in place,

31:25.541 --> 31:29.791
he's the likeliest to be able
to leave my house

31:29.875 --> 31:32.208
on his own abilities. Hmm?

31:42.625 --> 31:44.291
Thank you for taking me.

31:44.375 --> 31:46.333
Aw.

31:46.416 --> 31:49.083
Don't tell anybody I'm a good grandfather.

31:49.166 --> 31:51.625
-Everybody will want one.
-(laughs)

31:54.166 --> 31:59.333
Your mother has a tumor on her thyroid

31:59.416 --> 32:01.666
and is going to have it out.

32:02.750 --> 32:05.791
It might be malignant, hmm?

32:08.375 --> 32:09.625
Be nice to her.

32:10.791 --> 32:12.416
Okay.

32:12.500 --> 32:15.125
("My Opening Farewell"
by Jackson Browne playing)

32:18.083 --> 32:20.916
The biopsy proved
the tumor was malignant,

32:21.000 --> 32:23.916
so they cut it out,
along with her thyroid.

32:24.000 --> 32:26.791
No chemo, no radiation.

32:26.875 --> 32:29.916
They just cut it out,
and the cancer was gone.

32:30.000 --> 32:32.375
Sounds easier than it was.

32:32.458 --> 32:35.208
Nothing in my mom's life came easy.

32:39.750 --> 32:41.708
(vehicle approaches, brakes squeak)

32:46.875 --> 32:49.166
(engine shuts off)

32:54.000 --> 32:56.041
(birds chirping)

32:58.375 --> 32:59.791
(Mom groans)

33:12.125 --> 33:13.750
Do you want some water?

33:14.833 --> 33:17.541
I want you to succeed.

33:17.625 --> 33:19.458
What if I can't?

33:22.375 --> 33:26.916
As God is my witness,

33:27.000 --> 33:32.625
you are going to Yale.

33:36.291 --> 33:38.250
It's gonna cost $11,000.

33:38.333 --> 33:40.250
Yeah? Who says?

33:40.333 --> 33:41.958
Grandpa.

33:42.041 --> 33:43.833
(Mom scoffs)

33:46.250 --> 33:48.458
You mind if your mama believes in you?

33:50.708 --> 33:52.125
No.

33:53.166 --> 33:55.166
Something's wrong with my brain today.

33:55.250 --> 33:57.333
Wordy Gurdy has me stumped.

33:57.416 --> 33:59.333
What's Wordy Gurdy?

33:59.416 --> 34:00.833
It's a puzzle.

34:00.916 --> 34:04.083
They give you this half-assed clue,
and the answers rhyme.

34:04.166 --> 34:07.250
Like, uh... "Jane's vehicles"

34:07.333 --> 34:09.833
is, you know, "Fonda's Hondas."

34:09.916 --> 34:12.375
Life's hard enough without puzzles.

34:12.458 --> 34:14.750
Do puzzles, you don't get Alzheimer's.

34:14.833 --> 34:17.458
This one's bullshit.
"Richard's ingredients"?

34:17.541 --> 34:19.750
Who's Richard? Nixon?

34:19.833 --> 34:21.875
"Nixon's fixin's."

34:27.333 --> 34:30.041
-"Terrific Gary."
-"Super Cooper."

34:30.125 --> 34:32.958
("Dancing in the Moonlight"
by King Harvest playing)

34:34.041 --> 34:36.625
Oh, that's it-- kid's earned his stripes.

34:36.708 --> 34:38.791
-This kid's a prodigy.
-Gonna have to cut cards

34:38.875 --> 34:40.916
to see who loses their spot
in the bowling league.

34:41.000 --> 34:42.750
He's a prodigy, that kid.

34:42.833 --> 34:44.250
Where'd you learn that word?

35:19.416 --> 35:20.916
All right, one more.

35:21.000 --> 35:23.000
-Who else is coming?
-Pat.

35:23.083 --> 35:25.041
-Who's he?
-She.

35:25.125 --> 35:26.541
Your uncle's girlfriend.

35:26.625 --> 35:28.416
Ah, we all make mistakes.

35:28.500 --> 35:31.875
-Where do you think you're going?
-It's fucking Wednesday!

35:31.958 --> 35:34.916
I go fucking bowling
every fucking Wednesday! Fuck you!

35:35.000 --> 35:37.125
Fuck you, you stupid son of a bitch.
Fuck you!

35:37.208 --> 35:38.416
Fuck you! Learn how to fucking drive,
you twat.

35:38.500 --> 35:39.708
Fuck you!

35:39.791 --> 35:41.791
-Bitch.
-I see things are going well.

35:48.166 --> 35:49.750
Hiya.

35:55.458 --> 35:57.541
You must be young JR.

35:57.625 --> 35:59.708
What are you doing
hanging out with these bums?

35:59.791 --> 36:02.291
I get to go bowling
'cause I did the Wordy Gurdy.

36:02.375 --> 36:04.791
Aw, you must be the apple
of your mother's eye.

36:04.875 --> 36:06.750
I hope so, 'cause she's sad.

36:06.833 --> 36:09.208
Okay, that's enough.

36:23.250 --> 36:25.416
-(song stops)
-(bowling pins crashing)

36:25.500 --> 36:27.625
("Lonely Girl" by The Expressions playing)

36:27.708 --> 36:29.875
I don't know,
my feet are getting bigger, apparently.

36:29.958 --> 36:31.166
Size 12?

36:31.250 --> 36:34.250
Hey, Bobo, get me a size 13, will you?

36:35.500 --> 36:37.750
How's your mom doing with the cancer?

36:41.583 --> 36:42.791
You kidding me?

36:45.333 --> 36:47.416
A, it's in remission.

36:47.500 --> 36:49.875
Three, shut the fuck up.

36:51.208 --> 36:53.666
I'm sorry. You don't have to be
such a dick about it.

36:58.500 --> 37:00.541
I got you, uh, something.

37:00.625 --> 37:04.041
I was gonna hold on to it for a minute,
but I'll give it to you now.

37:04.125 --> 37:06.166
Here you go.

37:06.250 --> 37:07.833
Turn it over.

37:08.916 --> 37:11.375
That's Tom Seaver's autograph right there.

37:11.458 --> 37:13.666
-Thank you.
-Mm-hmm.

37:13.750 --> 37:16.750
Listen to me. Your mom is gonna be okay.

37:16.833 --> 37:18.166
You understand?

37:18.250 --> 37:19.958
I promise.

37:20.041 --> 37:22.958
You're not gonna see, uh,
Pat again, all right?

37:23.041 --> 37:24.625
She wasn't that bad.

37:24.708 --> 37:27.166
Well, it's kind of a last straw
kind of thing, you know?

37:27.250 --> 37:30.375
(sighs) Not exactly
the first inkblot on her ledger.

37:31.583 --> 37:34.416
You got to be able to do without people,
and they got to know it.

37:34.500 --> 37:35.833
It's either all in or nothing.

37:37.291 --> 37:38.541
Know what I mean?

37:38.625 --> 37:41.250
("It's Your Thing"
by The Isley Brothers playing)

37:41.333 --> 37:42.666
Go get a ball.

38:17.333 --> 38:18.333
Five.

38:27.041 --> 38:28.875
-Oh!
-Oh!

38:35.791 --> 38:37.458
(cheering)

38:43.083 --> 38:44.750
(song stops)

38:44.833 --> 38:47.666
"Laconic. Edict. Admonish.

38:47.750 --> 38:50.708
Platitude. Duplicity. Sanctimonious."

38:50.791 --> 38:52.625
Provisional. Strident.

38:52.708 --> 38:55.083
Bucolic. Fulcrum. Inimical.

38:55.166 --> 38:56.833
Jesuitical.

38:56.916 --> 38:58.958
Minion. Eclectic.

39:03.500 --> 39:04.916
Geez, Mom.

39:05.000 --> 39:06.916
-What? It's okay. I don't have lipstick.
-I mean...

39:09.708 --> 39:11.333
I won't get in.

39:12.416 --> 39:13.541
Yes, you will.

39:13.625 --> 39:16.166
Uncle Charlie says to go all in.

39:16.250 --> 39:18.458
Yeah, well, your uncle is
