Falling in love is a blessing.
Try to enjoy it.

55:05.958 --> 55:08.875
If you get your heart broken, you'll live.

55:11.041 --> 55:12.750
Ma, I have to ask you something.

55:12.833 --> 55:14.375
What?

55:18.541 --> 55:21.291
I need to go to Sidney's for Christmas.

55:46.833 --> 55:48.833
(vehicle approaching)

56:14.541 --> 56:16.541
(music playing faintly over radio)

56:23.666 --> 56:26.791
-What?
-What?

56:26.875 --> 56:30.458
It's Christmas in Connecticut,
with a Volvo.

56:32.625 --> 56:34.666
I'm never gonna train you out of it, am I?

56:34.750 --> 56:36.916
Train me out of what?

56:37.000 --> 56:39.875
Thinking things are more
than what they are.

56:42.916 --> 56:45.666
-You ever been to Westport?
-No.

56:48.625 --> 56:50.458
You ever fucked in a Volvo?

56:54.583 --> 56:58.083
There wasn't a thing
Sidney wouldn't do or try.

56:59.375 --> 57:01.583
She taught me about love,

57:01.666 --> 57:04.833
and that semester just flew by
for both of us.

57:04.916 --> 57:06.416
I wasn't naive.

57:06.500 --> 57:10.375
I knew that my first great love
probably wouldn't be my last.

57:10.458 --> 57:14.083
But there was something about her,
something different,

57:14.166 --> 57:16.291
something that gave me hope.

57:16.375 --> 57:18.791
("Rock Your Baby"
by George McCrae playing)

57:20.583 --> 57:22.166
(panting, grunting)

57:29.541 --> 57:31.791
(Sidney moaning loudly in other room)

57:38.458 --> 57:40.208
(moaning continues)

57:42.041 --> 57:43.583
(taking deep breaths)

57:47.208 --> 57:49.208
You okay?

57:49.291 --> 57:51.166
-Need a doctor?
-No.

57:51.250 --> 57:52.958
-I just need a minute.
-Okay.

58:02.208 --> 58:04.208
(song fades)

58:07.416 --> 58:09.375
(sighs)

58:11.958 --> 58:13.375
Morning, sport.

58:13.458 --> 58:15.250
(JR sighs) Morning.

58:16.916 --> 58:18.875
So, my parents...

58:20.000 --> 58:21.416
They already heard you.

58:21.500 --> 58:23.708
-Uh-oh.
-(laughs)

58:23.791 --> 58:25.333
They want to meet you.

58:34.875 --> 58:36.875
I think I should take you to the train.

58:37.958 --> 58:39.250
Why?

58:39.333 --> 58:42.208
It's very complicated.

58:42.291 --> 58:44.208
I'm feeling weird.

58:45.291 --> 58:47.500
I'm sorry I brought you for Christmas.

58:52.791 --> 58:54.708
I think I'm seeing someone else.

59:02.958 --> 59:04.583
I'll see you downstairs.

59:26.125 --> 59:28.375
SIDNEY'
Do you like scones, JR?

59:28.458 --> 59:30.333
Oh, I love scones, sir.

59:30.416 --> 59:33.083
-Call me Phil.
-Thanks, Phil.

59:33.166 --> 59:37.083
Since you can call him Phil,
I suppose you can call me Mrs. Lawson.

59:38.083 --> 59:39.708
(laughs)

59:50.416 --> 59:51.500
Mmm.

59:58.416 --> 1:00:01.625
(mouth full):
Well, Sidney tells me... Excuse me.

1:00:01.708 --> 1:00:03.708
(chuckles) So, Sidney...

1:00:03.791 --> 1:00:06.875
Sidney tells me you're both architects.

1:00:06.958 --> 1:00:09.791
Some people build houses.
We build dwellings.

1:00:09.875 --> 1:00:12.583
What's the difference except the word?

1:00:12.666 --> 1:00:15.958
I mean, I just failed an English exam,
but a house is a dwelling

1:00:16.041 --> 1:00:18.583
unless it's a cave,
and a dwelling is a house...

1:00:18.666 --> 1:00:21.291
They also run the magazine Dwellings.

1:00:21.375 --> 1:00:23.083
What?

1:00:23.166 --> 1:00:24.916
The magazine called Dwellings.

1:00:29.125 --> 1:00:30.458
Oh.

1:00:30.541 --> 1:00:32.416
I don't think you should dwell on it.

1:00:32.500 --> 1:00:34.708
-(light laughter)
-No.

1:00:36.166 --> 1:00:38.291
MRS.
I understand you have an absconded father

1:00:38.375 --> 1:00:41.583
who's nothing more to you
than a voice on the radio.

1:00:43.958 --> 1:00:45.958
Yeah, pretty much. (chuckles softly)

1:00:46.041 --> 1:00:48.666
Are you in psychotherapy?
I should think you would be.

1:00:48.750 --> 1:00:50.583
No psychotherapy, no.

1:00:50.666 --> 1:00:52.291
Surprisingly. (chuckles)

1:00:57.000 --> 1:00:58.750
What does your mother do, JR?

1:01:05.250 --> 1:01:08.625
She dwells in Manhasset,

1:01:08.708 --> 1:01:11.875
in a house with her parents,
who are both kind of nuts.

1:01:11.958 --> 1:01:13.916
And she's a secretary.

1:01:15.000 --> 1:01:19.791
And one of the things she always
loved to do was ride around

1:01:19.875 --> 1:01:21.916
looking at houses like this one

1:01:22.000 --> 1:01:25.208
and wonder what life must be like in them.

1:01:25.291 --> 1:01:27.291
Now I can tell her.

1:01:27.375 --> 1:01:29.458
Please do.

1:01:30.583 --> 1:01:32.583
I will.

1:01:33.666 --> 1:01:35.000
What do you study?

1:01:38.291 --> 1:01:41.041
You know, Phil, I study people.

1:01:41.125 --> 1:01:43.291
I think I've always studied people.

1:01:43.375 --> 1:01:45.875
And this is great.

1:01:45.958 --> 1:01:47.791
JR is a writer.

1:01:47.875 --> 1:01:49.833
I mean, what do you study at Yale?

1:01:50.916 --> 1:01:53.333
Usual fucking bullshit.
My mother wants me to be a lawyer.

1:01:53.416 --> 1:01:57.125
She sounds like a very intelligent woman,
if a trifle optimistic.

1:01:57.208 --> 1:01:58.916
(JR chuckles)

1:02:07.041 --> 1:02:08.958
Phil, you ever fucked in a Volvo?

1:02:10.208 --> 1:02:13.208
("50 Ways to Leave Your Lover"
by Paul Simon playing)

1:02:14.250 --> 1:02:17.000
And that was it-- dumped in Connecticut.

1:02:19.250 --> 1:02:24.125
I'd spend the next two years just focusing
on making something of myself.

1:02:24.208 --> 1:02:26.416
Being somebody.

1:02:26.500 --> 1:02:28.791
Somebody Sidney would want back.

1:02:32.041 --> 1:02:33.125
-Hey.
-Hi.

1:02:33.208 --> 1:02:34.375
Charlie!

1:03:47.875 --> 1:03:49.750
This seat taken?

1:03:49.833 --> 1:03:51.708
Look who it is. Sit down there.

1:03:52.791 --> 1:03:54.833
My senior year was gonna be epic.

1:03:54.916 --> 1:03:58.041
Writing for the paper, working at the bar.

1:03:58.125 --> 1:03:59.875
This was gonna be my year.

1:03:59.958 --> 1:04:01.791
I didn't need Sidney.

1:04:01.875 --> 1:04:03.708
In fact, fuck Sidney.

1:04:04.750 --> 1:04:06.500
Are you any good at writing?

1:04:06.583 --> 1:04:09.916
I fear that sometimes
the question is too little asked.

1:04:11.000 --> 1:04:12.625
I don't know.

1:04:12.708 --> 1:04:14.333
I have stuff in the Yale paper.

1:04:14.416 --> 1:04:16.125
A lot of people don't.

1:04:16.208 --> 1:04:17.583
Lot of people do. (chuckles)

1:04:20.041 --> 1:04:22.125
I always love to see you on this train.

1:04:23.208 --> 1:04:24.750
What's your main trouble?

1:04:24.833 --> 1:04:26.791
I'm just a poor boy who wants a rich girl.

1:04:26.875 --> 1:04:28.458
(chuckles softly)

1:04:28.541 --> 1:04:29.708
That's been done.

1:04:29.791 --> 1:04:31.208
She's not really rich.

1:04:31.291 --> 1:04:33.625
She's lower-upper-middle.

1:04:33.708 --> 1:04:36.708
Well, you never see the real rich.
They're invisible.

1:04:38.041 --> 1:04:40.791
Do you have plans in your head
to make something of yourself,

1:04:40.875 --> 1:04:42.708
go and sweep her away?

1:04:45.708 --> 1:04:47.125
Maybe.

1:04:47.208 --> 1:04:49.625
If she loved you, she'd take you poor.

1:04:51.208 --> 1:04:52.625
Heard it here first.

1:04:52.708 --> 1:04:54.000
(chuckles)

1:04:54.083 --> 1:04:56.041
I've heard it from someone else.

1:04:56.125 --> 1:04:59.208
Also, the Gatsby thing, you know?

1:05:00.333 --> 1:05:03.458
Well, what's your main theme?
Since it isn't really that one.

1:05:03.541 --> 1:05:07.000
The absent father. You know that one?

1:05:08.083 --> 1:05:11.125
Sure, how else do you think
people become priests?

1:05:11.208 --> 1:05:12.958
(chuckles)

1:05:17.333 --> 1:05:19.333
(knocking)

1:05:33.583 --> 1:05:35.583
(sighs)

1:05:41.375 --> 1:05:43.208
You know, you really had me going.

1:05:43.291 --> 1:05:45.208
About what?

1:05:45.291 --> 1:05:50.000
Well, for the past year--
year and a half, frankly--

1:05:50.083 --> 1:05:52.416
it's... my life's been hell.

1:05:53.625 --> 1:05:55.500
About me?

1:05:55.583 --> 1:05:57.291
-Yes, about you.
-(chuckles)

1:05:58.291 --> 1:06:00.166
What do you want from me?

1:06:01.333 --> 1:06:03.958
Well, we're seniors.

1:06:06.291 --> 1:06:07.958
I'm getting agita.

1:06:08.041 --> 1:06:12.041
Is agita the root of agitation?

1:06:12.125 --> 1:06:14.458
No. Men who want things are.

1:06:14.541 --> 1:06:18.083
You know, I think you think
I want something that I'm not thinking.

1:06:22.000 --> 1:06:24.166
Unless you want me to think it.

1:06:25.583 --> 1:06:27.416
I'm seeing someone.

1:06:29.500 --> 1:06:31.541
You got to be fucking kidding me.

1:06:32.625 --> 1:06:35.958
I can't explain it, really,
why I kept going back.

1:06:36.041 --> 1:06:38.500
She just had my number.

1:06:38.583 --> 1:06:42.000
All right,
so she gets agita, whatever that is.

1:06:42.083 --> 1:06:44.125
It's Yiddish for "nerves."

1:06:44.208 --> 1:06:47.750
All right, so she gets that
and she needs her space

1:06:47.833 --> 1:06:50.750
and her time and all that, right?

1:06:50.833 --> 1:06:52.958
So I have a question for you.

1:06:54.250 --> 1:06:56.250
What do you need?

1:06:58.708 --> 1:07:01.458
Look, I'm not a genius.
It's an obvious question.

1:07:01.541 --> 1:07:04.791
What do I want?
I want to be a writer, but I suck.

1:07:04.875 --> 1:07:07.583
Well, when you suck at writing,
that's when you become a journalist.

1:07:07.666 --> 1:07:09.333
I'm not going to law school.

1:07:09.416 --> 1:07:11.250
Neither am I.

1:07:14.125 --> 1:07:17.250
-My mom, she...
-Your mom wants you happy.

1:07:17.333 --> 1:07:19.625
Yeah, she does.

1:07:19.708 --> 1:07:21.833
Neither of us know how.

1:07:29.208 --> 1:07:31.750
Let's go back and get graduated.

1:07:32.833 --> 1:07:34.416
(chuckles)

1:07:36.375 --> 1:07:38.000
All right.

1:07:43.583 --> 1:07:45.791
-I'm here. I understand it's a big deal.
-Do you?

1:07:45.875 --> 1:07:47.791
-Yeah.
-He graduated from Yale.

1:07:47.875 --> 1:07:49.666
Your father graduated from Dartmouth.

1:07:50.750 --> 1:07:53.541
So, without further ado,
let's bring them in.

1:07:53.625 --> 1:07:55.708
Ladies and gentlemen,
let's give a warm welcome

1:07:55.791 --> 1:07:58.541
to the Yale class of 1986.

1:07:58.625 --> 1:08:01.541
(Valentin Haussmann's
"Polnischer Tanz, Deutscher Tanz" playing)

1:08:07.208 --> 1:08:09.208
(applause)

1:08:21.000 --> 1:08:23.416
-(knocking)
-There's a call for you.

1:08:31.541 --> 1:08:33.375
Hello?

1:08:33.458 --> 1:08:35.083
Remember me?

1:08:36.458 --> 1:08:37.875
Hey, Dad.

1:08:37.958 --> 1:08:39.958
I-I-I didn't make it, as you know.

1:08:40.041 --> 1:08:42.208
Uh, no... no surprise there.

1:08:42.291 --> 1:08:46.333
Uh, but I did want to tell you that, uh...

1:08:46.416 --> 1:08:48.166
I quit drinking.

1:08:48.250 --> 1:08:51.166
And, uh, I've been here and there...

1:08:52.666 --> 1:08:54.666
(laughs) â€¦apologizing

1:08:54.750 --> 1:08:58.375
and... you made the list.

1:08:58.458 --> 1:09:01.291
-Wow.
-Oh, come on. Don't fuck with me.

1:09:02.958 --> 1:09:04.583
Hey, I'm glad you made it.

1:09:04.666 --> 1:09:06.625
Uh, I was worried.

1:09:06.708 --> 1:09:09.000
College ain't for everybody.

1:09:09.083 --> 1:09:12.375
It was for Mom, but you got her pregnant.

1:09:12.458 --> 1:09:16.250
Yes, well, we all have to paddle
our own canoe, JR.

1:09:16.333 --> 1:09:19.416
Seems like your mother's got you
paddling hers a little bit.

1:09:20.500 --> 1:09:24.375
I think she's been paddling both of ours
for a very long time.

1:09:27.541 --> 1:09:28.958
Maybe.

1:09:30.458 --> 1:09:33.250
Uh, all right, well, I'm on the air
in 15 and change.

1:09:33.333 --> 1:09:34.750
I got to go.

1:09:34.833 --> 1:09:37.041
-Where are you?
-(click, dial tone)

1:09:42.750 --> 1:09:44.583
What law schools are you looking at?

1:09:45.666 --> 1:09:46.958
None.

1:09:47.041 --> 1:09:48.791
I'm gonna be a novelist.

1:09:52.791 --> 1:09:54.375
Where you gonna live?

1:09:54.458 --> 1:09:57.750
At Grandpa's, like everybody.

1:09:57.833 --> 1:09:59.250
We all go to Grandpa's.

1:09:59.333 --> 1:10:03.000
I mean, I-I know you think this is
supposed to change everything, but...

1:10:03.083 --> 1:10:04.416
You have to have a job.

1:10:04.500 --> 1:10:07.166
I will have a job-- writing a novel.

1:10:09.333 --> 1:10:11.583
Publishing is going more towards memoir.

1:10:11.666 --> 1:10:13.375
(chuckles) That's true.

1:10:19.708 --> 1:10:21.708
Here.

1:10:21.791 --> 1:10:23.416
Is this for Sidney?

1:10:23.500 --> 1:10:25.250
No.

1:10:25.333 --> 1:10:26.875
Open it.

1:10:34.125 --> 1:10:35.333
It's a Yale ring.

1:10:35.416 --> 1:10:37.916
I don't like male jewelry, but I thought,

1:10:38.000 --> 1:10:40.750
since the Musketeers
actually did this together...

1:10:41.833 --> 1:10:43.541
It's for you.

1:10:49.583 --> 1:10:51.583
(JR chuckles)

1:10:59.875 --> 1:11:01.708
Jesus, fuck.

1:11:01.791 --> 1:11:04.541
Symbolically,
you just married your mother.

1:11:04.625 --> 1:11:06.541
-Whoa. Take it easy.
-All right, all right, all right.

1:11:06.625 --> 1:11:09.375
So let's say... let's say you closed
the circle with one parent, right?

1:11:09.458 --> 1:11:11.291
-Yeah. Yeah.
-Maybe.

1:11:11.375 --> 1:11:13.125
What about The Voice?

1:11:13.208 --> 1:11:15.458
-I don't even know where he is.
-The Voice...

1:11:15.541 --> 1:11:18.666
locked in a downward spiral
since the Carter administration.

1:11:19.833 --> 1:11:23.083
So both you assholes just graduated?

1:11:23.166 --> 1:11:25.833
Charlie, back 'em up on me.

1:11:25.916 --> 1:11:27.458
-Aw.
-Thanks, Chief.

1:11:27.541 --> 1:11:30.500
So, how much do they get
for a Yale education these days?

1:11:30.583 --> 1:11:32.000
Oh, it's 60 grand.

1:11:32.083 --> 1:11:34.958
-60?
-JR got grants and scholarships.

1:11:35.041 --> 1:11:37.250
Wesley, you were a full-ticket guy?

1:11:37.333 --> 1:11:38.541
All right, answer me this.

1:11:38.625 --> 1:11:42.041
What year... was the Magna Carta signed?

1:11:43.125 --> 1:11:45.041
-I don't know.
-I don't fucking know.

1:11:45.125 --> 1:11:47.958
-Survey says...
-1215.

1:11:48.041 --> 1:11:50.541
It's the foundation of English law.
You should know it.

1:11:50.625 --> 1:11:52.708
-Bulwark against tyranny.
-King John.

1:11:52.791 --> 1:11:54.625
-- That's right.
-- At this point, Chief,

1:11:54.708 --> 1:11:57.125
-I don't give a shit.
-He doesn't give a shit.

1:11:57.208 --> 1:12:00.000
Kid, I'm just trying to keep you
out of the ruling classes. That's all.

1:12:00.083 --> 1:12:01.750
Too late, Chief. Too late.

1:12:01.833 --> 1:12:04.833
$60,000. My house cost $12,000.

1:12:04.916 --> 1:12:07.875
-Your house cost $7,000.
-My house cost $7,000.

1:12:10.791 --> 1:12:12.958
I was kind of into
the "clean break" idea.

1:12:13.041 --> 1:12:14.666
SIDNEY (laughs):
We can be friends.

1:12:14.750 --> 1:12:16.708
Just not romantic or sexual.

1:12:16.791 --> 1:12:18.833
That sounds appealing.

1:12:18.916 --> 1:12:20.333
(Sidney laughs)

1:12:20.416 --> 1:12:22.791
So, what are you doing?

1:12:22.875 --> 1:12:24.291
I'm at the bar a lot.

1:12:24.375 --> 1:12:26.458
I'm working on my novel.

1:12:28.125 --> 1:12:30.166
Publishing is heading towards memoir.

1:12:30.250 --> 1:12:32.833
People have been saying that. Yeah.

1:12:32.916 --> 1:12:34.875
So, how many pages do you have?

1:12:36.708 --> 1:12:38.041
Many.

1:12:39.166 --> 1:12:40.875
Have you applied to newspapers?

1:12:40.958 --> 1:12:43.125
-Yeah. Yeah.
-You have clips?

1:12:43.208 --> 1:12:44.958
You contacted The New York Times?

1:12:45.041 --> 1:12:47.500
Would you like it if I was at The Times?

1:12:48.750 --> 1:12:50.875
I love you anyway.

1:12:50.958 --> 1:12:52.750
I just don't want a relationship.

1:12:52.833 --> 1:12:54.250
But you have a relationship.

1:12:54.333 --> 1:12:57.250
It's just not romantic or sexual.

1:13:03.500 --> 1:13:05.708
I think The Times is probably
out of my league.

1:13:07.375 --> 1:13:09.208
Was Yale out of your league?

1:13:10.291 --> 1:13:12.625
-Can we just go to your place?
-No.

1:13:14.166 --> 1:13:15.708
I live with him.

1:13:20.333 --> 1:13:23.625
So, Sidney saw you
in your reduced condition.

1:13:24.708 --> 1:13:26.833
-But she was checking up on you.
-Yeah.

1:13:26.916 --> 1:13:29.000
She was trying to see if you had
your shit together.

1:13:29.083 --> 1:13:31.458
(laughing):
Uh...

1:13:31.541 --> 1:13:35.291
I don't even have any shit
to get together.

1:13:35.375 --> 1:13:38.166
-I don't. I don't have anything.
-Hey. Hey, hey, listen.

1:13:38.250 --> 1:13:41.666
What did I tell you
about the male sciences?

1:13:41.750 --> 1:13:43.375
-Remember that?
-Yeah.

1:13:43.458 --> 1:13:45.375
-Right? Have a job.
-Right.

1:13:45.458 --> 1:13:46.625
-Have a car.
-Yeah.

1:13:46.708 --> 1:13:48.750
-Put all your shit in it.
-I don't have any of that.

1:13:48.833 --> 1:13:52.583
So you can be independent,
and then somebody might want you.

1:13:52.666 --> 1:13:55.208
And if they don't,
you get the fuck out of there.

1:13:57.166 --> 1:13:58.541
Right?

1:13:58.625 --> 1:14:00.291
(JR breathing deeply)

1:14:01.375 --> 1:14:04.208
-(phone rings)
-New York Times.

1:14:04.291 --> 1:14:06.375
Yes. Can I tell him who's calling?

1:14:08.125 --> 1:14:09.458
Take care.

1:14:09.541 --> 1:14:11.541
(indistinct chatter)

1:14:12.916 --> 1:14:14.875
-(phone rings)
-New York Times.

1:14:15.916 --> 1:14:17.083
-Hi. Are you JR?
-Yes.

1:14:17.166 --> 1:14:18.625
Yeah, you can come with me.

1:14:19.708 --> 1:14:22.041
We all like your clips from New Haven.

1:14:22.125 --> 1:14:23.875
Where are you working now?

1:14:23.958 --> 1:14:25.875
I'm writing fiction, I think.

1:14:25.958 --> 1:14:29.583
And I work at a family business.

1:14:30.583 --> 1:14:33.291
It's a hospitality business.

